Definition 3.1. A $\overline{\mathbb{K}}$-extended L-convex set $\mathbf{D}$ is a pair $({\textup{Ind}(\mathbf{D})},\mathbf{D}_{0})$ where • ${\textup{Ind}(\mathbf{D})}$ is a set called the index set of $\mathbf{D}$; • $\mathbf{D}_{0}$ is a subset of $\overline{\mathbb{K}}^{\textup{Ind}(\mathbf{D})}$ called the underlying set of $\mathbf{D}$; such that the following axioms hold: $\qquad$(Order completeness) $\bigvee_{p\in S}p,\ \bigwedge_{p\in S}p\in\mathbf{D}_{0}\quad(\forall S% \subseteq\mathbf{D}_{0})$; $\qquad$(Weight completeness) $p+\alpha\cdot\textbf{1}\in\mathbf{D}_{0}\quad(\forall p\in\mathbf{D}_{0},\ % \forall\alpha\in\mathbb{K}\cup\{-\infty,\infty\})$.
Definition 2.17. Let $\mathcal{V}=(\mathcal{V}_{0},\otimes,e)$ be an SM-P, and $\mathcal{A}=$ $(\textup{Ob}(\mathcal{A}),\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}})$ and $\mathcal{B}=(\textup{Ob}(\mathcal{B}),\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}})$ be $\mathcal{V}$-categories. A $\mathcal{V}$-functor $F\colon\mathcal{A}\longrightarrow\mathcal{B}$ from $\mathcal{A}$ to $\mathcal{B}$ is a map $\textup{Ob}(F)\colon\textup{Ob}(\mathcal{A})\longrightarrow\textup{Ob}(% \mathcal{B})$ between the sets of objects with the following property: $\ \ $(Increasing condition) $\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(a,a^{\prime})\sqsubseteq\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}}% \big{(}\textup{Ob}(F)(a),\textup{Ob}(F)(a^{\prime})\big{)}$ $(\forall a,a^{\prime}\in\textup{Ob}(\mathcal{A}))$. In case a stronger condition $\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(a,a^{\prime})=\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}}\big{(}% \textup{Ob}(F)(a),\textup{Ob}(F)(a^{\prime})\big{)}\quad(\forall a,a^{\prime}% \in\textup{Ob}(\mathcal{A}))$ holds, $F$ is called a fully faithful $\mathcal{V}$-functor. $\mathcal{A}$ is called the domain of $F$ and $\mathcal{B}$ the codomain of $F$. We denote the set of all $\mathcal{V}$-functors from $\mathcal{A}$ to $\mathcal{B}$ by $[\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B}]_{0}$.
Definition 2.2. A symmetric closed poset (SC-P) $\mathcal{V}$ is a triple $(\mathcal{V}_{0},[-,-],e)$ where • $\mathcal{V}_{0}=(\mathcal{V}_{0},\sqsubseteq)$ is a poset called the underlying poset; • $[-,-]\colon\mathcal{V}_{0}^{\textup{op}}\times\mathcal{V}_{0}\longrightarrow% \mathcal{V}_{0}$ is a binary operation on $\mathcal{V}_{0}$ called the internal-hom; • $e$ is an element of $\mathcal{V}_{0}$ called the unit element; such that the following axioms hold: $\qquad$(Monotonicity of $[-,-]$) $y\sqsupseteq y^{\prime}$ and $z\sqsubseteq z^{\prime}$ imply $[y,z]\sqsubseteq[y^{\prime},z^{\prime}]\quad(\forall y,y^{\prime},z,z^{\prime}% \in\mathcal{V}_{0})$; $\qquad$(Composition law) $[y,z]\sqsubseteq[[x,y],[x,z]]\quad(\forall x,y,z\in\mathcal{V}_{0})$; $\qquad$(Unit law for $[-,-]$) $z=[e,z]\quad(\forall z\in\mathcal{V}_{0})$; $\qquad$(Commutative law for $[-,-]$) $x\sqsubseteq[y,z]\iff y\sqsubseteq[x,z]\quad(\forall x,y,z\in\mathcal{V}_{0})$. A symmetric closed complete lattice (SC-CL) is an SC-P whose underlying poset $\mathcal{V}_{0}$ is a complete lattice.
Definition 2.41. Let $\mathcal{V}=(\mathcal{V}_{0},\otimes,[-,-],e)$ be an SMC-CL, and $\mathcal{A}=(\textup{Ob}(\mathcal{A}),\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}})$ be a $\mathcal{V}$-category. A presheaf $P$ on $\mathcal{A}$ is a $\mathcal{V}$-functor $P\colon\mathcal{A}^{\textup{op}}\longrightarrow\mathcal{V}$, that is, a map $\textup{Ob}(P)\colon\textup{Ob}(\mathcal{A})\longrightarrow\mathcal{V}_{0}$ satisfying $\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(a,b)\sqsubseteq[P(b),P(a)]$ for every $a,b\in\textup{Ob}(\mathcal{A})$. A copresheaf $Q$ on $\mathcal{A}$ is a $\mathcal{V}$-functor $Q\colon\mathcal{A}\longrightarrow\mathcal{V}$, that is, a map $\textup{Ob}(Q)\colon\textup{Ob}(\mathcal{A})\longrightarrow\mathcal{V}_{0}$ satisfying $\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(a,b)\sqsubseteq[Q(a),Q(b)]$ for every $a,b\in\textup{Ob}(\mathcal{A})$. We call the functor category ${\textup{Fun}(\mathcal{A}^{\textup{op}},\mathcal{V})}$ the presheaf category of $\mathcal{A}$, and the category ${\textup{Fun}(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{V})}^{\textup{op}}$ the op-copresheaf category of $\mathcal{A}$.
Definition 3.4 ([8]). Let $V$ be a finite set. A subset $D\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{V}$ is an L-convex polyhedron if the following hold: $\qquad$(Nonemptiness) $D\neq\emptyset$; $\qquad$(Closedness) $D$ is a closed subset of $\mathbb{R}^{V}$; $\qquad$(SBS$[\mathbb{R}]$) $p\land q,\ p\lor q\in D\quad(\forall p,q\in D)$; $\qquad$(TRS$[\mathbb{R}]$) $p+\alpha\cdot\textbf{1}\in D\quad(\forall p\in D,\ \forall\alpha\in\mathbb{R})$.
Definition 2.19. Let $\mathcal{V}$ be an SM-P, and $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ be $\mathcal{V}$-categories. A $\mathcal{V}$-functor $F\colon\mathcal{A}\longrightarrow\mathcal{B}$ from $\mathcal{A}$ to $\mathcal{B}$ is an isomorphism if there exists a $\mathcal{V}$-functor (called its inverse) $G\colon\mathcal{B}\longrightarrow\mathcal{A}$ from $\mathcal{B}$ to $\mathcal{A}$ such that $G\circ F=1_{\mathcal{A}}$ and $F\circ G=1_{\mathcal{B}}$ hold. If there is an isomorphism between $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$, then they are said to be isomorphic and written as $\mathcal{A}\cong\mathcal{B}$.
Definition 2.1. A symmetric monoidal poset (SM-P) $\mathcal{V}$ is a triple $(\mathcal{V}_{0},\otimes,e)$ where • $\mathcal{V}_{0}=(\mathcal{V}_{0},\sqsubseteq)$ is a poset called the underlying poset; • $\otimes\colon\mathcal{V}_{0}\times\mathcal{V}_{0}\longrightarrow\mathcal{V}_{0}$ is a binary operation on $\mathcal{V}_{0}$ called the tensor product; • $e$ is an element of $\mathcal{V}_{0}$ called the unit element; such that the following axioms hold: $\qquad$(Monotonicity of $\otimes$) $x\sqsubseteq x^{\prime}$ and $y\sqsubseteq y^{\prime}$ imply $x\otimes y\sqsubseteq x^{\prime}\otimes y^{\prime}\quad(\forall x,x^{\prime},y% ,y^{\prime}\in\mathcal{V}_{0})$; $\qquad$(Associative law) $x\otimes(y\otimes z)=(x\otimes y)\otimes z\quad(\forall x,y,z\in\mathcal{V}_{0})$; $\qquad$(Unit law for $\otimes$) $e\otimes x=x=x\otimes e\quad(\forall x\in\mathcal{V}_{0})$; $\qquad$(Commutative law for $\otimes$) $x\otimes y=y\otimes x\quad(\forall x,y\in\mathcal{V}_{0})$. A symmetric monoidal complete lattice (SM-CL) is an SM-P whose underlying poset $\mathcal{V}_{0}$ is a complete lattice.
Definition 2.21. Let $\mathcal{V}=(\mathcal{V}_{0},\otimes,e)$ be an SM-P, and $\mathcal{A}=$ $(\textup{Ob}(\mathcal{A}),\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}})$ and $\mathcal{B}=(\textup{Ob}(\mathcal{B}),\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}})$ be $\mathcal{V}$-categories. The set $[\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B}]_{0}$ of all $\mathcal{V}$-functors from $\mathcal{A}$ to $\mathcal{B}$ admits a canonical relation $\Rightarrow$ defined as follows: $F\Rightarrow G\iff e\sqsubseteq\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}}\big{(}F(a),G(a)\big{% )}\quad(\forall a\in\textup{Ob}(\mathcal{A}));$ where $F,G\colon\mathcal{A}\longrightarrow\mathcal{B}$ are $\mathcal{V}$-functors. We call $\Rightarrow$ the canonical ordering on $[\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B}]_{0}$.
Definition 2.47. The $\mathcal{V}$-functor $Y$ is called the Yoneda embedding, and $\overline{Y}$ the co-Yoneda embedding.
Definition 2.11. Let $\mathcal{V}=(\mathcal{V}_{0},\otimes,e)$ be an SM-P. A $\mathcal{V}$-category $\mathcal{A}$ is a pair $(\textup{Ob}(\mathcal{A}),$ $\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}})$ where • $\textup{Ob}(\mathcal{A})$ is the set of objects of $\mathcal{A}$; • $\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}$ is a map which assigns for each pair $a,b$ of objects of $\mathcal{A}$, an element $\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(a,b)$ of $\mathcal{V}_{0}$ called its hom-object; such that the following axioms hold: $\qquad$(Composition law) $\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(a,b)\otimes\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(b,c)% \sqsubseteq\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(a,c)\quad(\forall a,b,c\in\textup{Ob}(% \mathcal{A}))$; $\qquad$(Identity law) $e\sqsubseteq\textup{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(a,a)\quad(\forall a\in\textup{Ob}(% \mathcal{A}))$.
Definition 3.3 ([8]). Let $V$ be a finite set. A subset $D\subseteq\mathbb{Z}^{V}$ is an L-convex set if the following hold: $\qquad$(Nonemptiness) $D\neq\emptyset$; $\qquad$(SBS$[\mathbb{Z}]$) $p\land q,\ p\lor q\in D\quad(\forall p,q\in D)$; $\qquad$(TRS$[\mathbb{Z}]$) $p+\alpha\cdot\textbf{1}\in D\quad(\forall p\in D,\ \forall\alpha\in\mathbb{Z})$.
Definition 2.3. A symmetric monoidal closed poset (SMC-P) $\mathcal{V}$ is a quadruple $(\mathcal{V}_{0},\otimes,$ $[-,-],e)$ where • the triple $(\mathcal{V}_{0},\otimes,e)$ is an SM-P; • the triple $(\mathcal{V}_{0},[-,-],e)$ is an SC-P; such that these two structures are related as follows: $\qquad$(Adjointness relation) $x\otimes y\sqsubseteq z\iff x\sqsubseteq[y,z]\quad(\forall x,y,z\in\mathcal{V}% _{0})$. A symmetric monoidal closed complete lattice (SMC-CL) is an SMC-P whose underlying poset $\mathcal{V}_{0}$ is a complete lattice.
Definition 2.40. The $\mathcal{V}$-category ${\textup{Fun}(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B})}$ is called a functor category, $\mathcal{A}$ its domain and $\mathcal{B}$ its codomain.
Definition 3.8. Let $\mathbf{D}=({\textup{Ind}(\mathbf{D})},\mathbf{D}_{0})$ and $\mathbf{E}=({\textup{Ind}(\mathbf{E})},\mathbf{E}_{0})$ be $\overline{\mathbb{K}}$-extended L-convex sets. The set ${\llbracket\mathbf{D},\mathbf{E}\rrbracket}$ of all homomorphisms from $\mathbf{D}$ to $\mathbf{E}$ admits a canonical relation $\Rightarrow$ defined as follows: $\Phi\Rightarrow\Psi\iff\Phi_{0}(p)\geq\Psi_{0}(p)\quad(\forall p\in\mathbf{D}_% {0}),$ where $\Phi,\Psi\colon\mathbf{D}\longrightarrow\mathbf{E}$ are homomorphisms and $\geq$ is the coordinate-wise order on $\mathbf{E}_{0}$. We call $\Rightarrow$ the canonical ordering on ${\llbracket\mathbf{D},\mathbf{E}\rrbracket}_{0}$.
Definition 3.6. Let $\mathbf{D}=({\textup{Ind}(\mathbf{D})},\mathbf{D}_{0})$ and $\mathbf{E}=({\textup{Ind}(\mathbf{E})},\mathbf{E}_{0})$ be $\overline{\mathbb{K}}$-extended L-convex sets. A homomorphism $\Phi\colon\mathbf{D}\longrightarrow\mathbf{E}$ from $\mathbf{D}$ to $\mathbf{E}$ is a map ${\textup{Ind}(\Phi)}\colon{\textup{Ind}(\mathbf{E})}\longrightarrow{\textup{% Ind}(\mathbf{D})}$ from the index set of $\mathbf{E}$ to that of $\mathbf{D}$, such that for all $p\in\mathbf{D}_{0}$, the element $\Phi_{0}(p)\in\overline{\mathbb{K}}^{\textup{Ind}(\mathbf{E})}$ given by $\Phi_{0}(p)=p\circ{\textup{Ind}(\Phi)}\colon{\textup{Ind}(\mathbf{E})}\overset% {{\textup{Ind}(\Phi)}}{\longrightarrow}{\textup{Ind}(\mathbf{D})}\overset{p}{% \longrightarrow}\mathbb{K}\cup\{-\infty,\infty\}$ is an element of $\mathbf{E}_{0}$. $\mathbf{D}$ is called the domain of $\Phi$ and $\mathbf{E}$ the codomain of $\Phi$. We denote the set of all homomorphisms from $\mathbf{D}$ to $\mathbf{E}$ by ${\llbracket\mathbf{D},\mathbf{E}\rrbracket}_{0}$.
Definition 3.7. Let $\mathbf{D}$ and $\mathbf{E}$ be $\overline{\mathbb{K}}$-extended L-convex sets. A homomorphism $\Phi\colon\mathbf{D}\longrightarrow\mathbf{E}$ from $\mathbf{D}$ to $\mathbf{E}$ is an isomorphism if there exists a homomorphism (called its inverse) $\Psi\colon\mathbf{E}\longrightarrow\mathbf{D}$ from $\mathbf{E}$ to $\mathbf{D}$ such that $\Psi\circ\Phi=1_{\mathbf{D}}$ and $\Phi\circ\Psi=1_{\mathbf{E}}$ hold, where $1_{\mathbf{D}}$ and $1_{\mathbf{E}}$ are the identity homomorphisms on $\mathbf{D}$ and $\mathbf{E}$, respectively. If there is an isomorphism between $\mathbf{D}$ and $\mathbf{E}$, then they are said to be isomorphic and written as $\mathbf{D}\cong\mathbf{E}$.
Definition 1 A dagger category is a category $\mathscr{C}$ equipped with an functor $(-)^{\dagger}:\mathscr{C}^{\operatorname{op}}\to\mathscr{C}$ satisfying that $\operatorname{id}_{X}^{\dagger}=\operatorname{id}_{X}$ and $f^{\dagger\dagger}=f$ for all identities $X\xrightarrow{\operatorname{id}_{X}}X$ and morphisms $X\xrightarrow{f}Y$.
Definition 8 A functional $\mathscr{C}(X,Y)\times\mathscr{C}(P,Q)\xrightarrow{\psi_{\ddagger}}\mathscr{C}% (X,Y)$ is parametrized fixed point adjoint to a functional $\mathscr{C}(X,Y)\times\mathscr{C}(P,Q)\xrightarrow{\psi}\mathscr{C}(X,Y)$ iff $(\operatorname{pfix}\psi)(p)^{\dagger}=(\operatorname{pfix}\psi_{\ddagger})(p^% {\dagger})$.
Definition 4 An involutive (symmetric) monoidal category is a (symmetric) monoidal category $\mathscr{V}$ which is also involutive, such that the involution is a monoidal functor, and $\operatorname{id}\Rightarrow\overline{\overline{(-)}}$ is a monoidal natural isomorphism.
Definition 6 For a $\mathbf{DCPO}$-$\dagger$-category $\mathscr{C}$, define $\mathbf{DcpoOp}(\mathscr{C})$ to have as objects all objects $\Theta,\Lambda$ of $\mathbf{DCPO}$ of the form $\mathscr{C}(X,Y)$, $\mathscr{C}^{\operatorname{op}}(X,Y)$ (for all objects $X,Y$ of $\mathscr{C}$), $1$, and $\Theta\times\Lambda$ (with $1$ initial object of $\mathbf{DCPO}$, and $-\times-$ the cartesian product), and as morphisms all continuous functions between these.
Definition 5 Say that a dagger structure on $\mathbf{DCPO}$-category is monotone if the dagger is locally monotone, i.e., if $f\sqsubseteq g$ implies $f^{\dagger}\sqsubseteq g^{\dagger}$ for all $f$ and $g$.
Definition 7 A functional $\mathscr{C}(Y,X)\xrightarrow{\varphi_{\ddagger}}\mathscr{C}(Y,X)$ is fixed point adjoint to a functional $\mathscr{C}(X,Y)\xrightarrow{\varphi}\mathscr{C}(X,Y)$ iff $(\operatorname{fix}\varphi)^{\dagger}=\operatorname{fix}\varphi_{\ddagger}$.
Definition 2 An iteration category is a cartesian category with a parametrized fixed point operator satisfying all identities (of the parametrized fixed point operator) that hold in $\mathbf{DCPO}$.
Definition 3 A category $\mathscr{V}$ is involutive if it is equipped with a functor $\mathscr{V}\xrightarrow{\overline{(-)}}\mathscr{V}$ (the involution) and a natural isomorphism $\operatorname{id}\xRightarrow{\iota}\overline{\overline{(-)}}$ satisfying $\iota_{\overline{X}}=\overline{\iota_{X}}$.
Definition 2.6. We say that a full subcategory $\mathcal{L}$ of a category $\mathcal{K}$ is reflective if the inclusion functor $\mathcal{L}\to\mathcal{K}$ has a left adjoint. Equivalently: for every $K$ in $\mathcal{K}$ there is a reflection arrow $r_{K}:K\to L$, $L$ in $\mathcal{L}$, so that any $K\to L^{\prime}$, $L^{\prime}$ in $\mathcal{L}$, factors uniquely through $r_{K}$. We say that $\mathcal{L}$ is a weakly reflective subcategory if it admits a weak reflection arrow $r_{K}$ for each $K$ in $\mathcal{K}$—as above, but removing the requirement that the factorizations be unique.
Definition 2.2. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a category. (1) A monomorphism (or mono, for short) is a morphism $f$ such that $fg_{1}=fg_{2}$ always implies $g_{1}=g_{2}$. Dually, an epimorphism (epi, for short) is a morphism $f$ such that $g_{1}f=g_{2}f$ implies $g_{1}=g_{2}$ for any $g_{1}$ and $g_{2}$. (2) Suppose we have maps $A\xrightarrow{i}B\xrightarrow{r}A$ with $ri=\operatorname{id}_{A}$. Then we call $r$ a retraction (or split epimorphism) and we call $i$ a section (or split monomorphism). The map $r$ witnesses that $A$ is a retract of $B$.
Definition 2.7. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a category and let $\mathcal{M}$ be a class of morphisms of $\mathcal{K}$. (1) $\operatorname{Po}(\mathcal{M})$ is the class of pushouts of morphisms in $\mathcal{M}$; that is, a morphism $g$ is in $\operatorname{Po}(\mathcal{M})$ if and only if it is an isomorphism or there exists $f\in\mathcal{M}$ and a pushout square of the form:
Definition 2.1. For a regular cardinal $\lambda$, an object $A$ in a category $\mathcal{K}$ is called $\lambda$-presentable if the functor $\operatorname{Hom}(A,-):\mathcal{K}\to\operatorname{\bf Set}$ preserves $\lambda$-directed colimits (i.e. colimits indexed by a $\lambda$-directed poset, which is a poset where every subset of cardinality strictly less than $\lambda$ has an upper bound). A category $\mathcal{K}$ is $\lambda$-accessible if it has $\lambda$-directed colimits, only a set up to isomorphism of $\lambda$-presentable objects, and every object is a $\lambda$-directed colimit of $\lambda$-presentable objects. The category $\mathcal{K}$ is locally $\lambda$-presentable if it is complete and cocomplete and $\lambda$-accessible. A category is accessible [locally presentable] if it is $\lambda$-accessible [locally $\lambda$-presentable] for some $\lambda$. When $\lambda=\aleph_{0}$, we also talk of a finitely presentable object, and of a finitely accessible [locally finitely presentable] category.
Definition 2.3. A subcategory $\mathcal{L}$ of a category $\mathcal{K}$ is: (1) isomorphism-closed (or replete) if whenever $A$ is an object of $\mathcal{L}$ and $f:A\to B$ is an isomorphism, we have that $f$ and $B$ are both in $\mathcal{K}$. (2) closed under limits in $\mathcal{K}$ if whenever $D:I\to\mathcal{L}$ is a diagram in $\mathcal{L}$ and $(A\xrightarrow{f_{i}}D_{i})_{i\in I}$ is a limit cone in $\mathcal{K}$, then $(A\xrightarrow{f_{i}}D_{i})_{i\in I}$ is a limit cone in $\mathcal{L}$. Similarly define closure under any class of (co)limits, such as colimits, $\lambda$-directed colimits, etc.
Definition 5.5. Let $(X,\pi,\leq_{X})$ be a Priestley space and $(Y,\tau,\leq_{Y})$ a compact ordered space. We say a continuous function $q\colon X\to Y^{\downarrow}$ is an interpolating decomposition of $X$ over $Y$ if, for all $x_{1},x_{2}\in X$, if $x_{1}\leq_{X}x_{2}$, then there exists $z\in X$ such that $q(x_{1})\leq_{Y}q(z)$, $q(x_{2})\leq_{Y}q(z)$ and $x_{1}\leq_{X}z\leq_{X}x_{2}$.
Definition 3.2. Let $F$ be a sheaf of $\mathcal{V}$-algebras over a space $Y$ and let $p\colon E\to Y$ be the corresponding étale space. Then $F$ is called soft if, for every compact saturated $K\subseteq Y$ and continuous section $s\colon K\to E$ of $p$, there exists a global section $t$ of $p$ such that $t|_{K}=s$.
Definition 3.1. A sheaf representation of a $\mathcal{V}$-algebra $A$ is a sheaf $F$ such that $A$ is isomorphic to $FY$, the algebra of global sections of $F$.
Definition 3.6 (Sheaf associated to a homomorphism). Let $\vartheta\colon(\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}Y^{\uparrow})^{\mathrm{op}}\to% \operatorname{\mathrm{Con}}(A)$ be a frame homomorphism such that any two congruences in the image of $\vartheta$ commute. For each $y\in Y$, denote by $\vartheta_{y}$ the congruence $\vartheta({\uparrow}y)$. Define the disjoint union of $\mathcal{V}$-algebras $E_{\vartheta}:=\bigsqcup_{y\in Y}A/{\vartheta_{y}},$ and let $p\colon E_{\vartheta}\to Y$ be the function which maps each summand $A/{\vartheta_{y}}$ to its index $y$. For each $a\in A$, denote by $s_{a}\colon Y\to E_{\vartheta}$ the function defined by $s_{a}(y):=a/{\vartheta_{y}}$, for $y\in Y$. Equip $E_{\vartheta}$ with the topology generated by the collection $\mathcal{B}=\{s_{a}(U)\ |\ a\in A,U\in\Omega Y^{\uparrow}\}.$ Note that $p\colon E_{\vartheta}\to Y^{\uparrow}$ is a continuous function, since for any $U\in\Omega Y^{\uparrow}$, we have $p^{-1}(U)=\bigcup_{a\in A}s_{a}(U)$. Denote by $F_{\vartheta}$ the sheaf of local sections of $p$.
Definition 1. The strategy $\varphi$ is an open-loop strategy if, and only if, $I(\varphi)=0$. Otherwise $\varphi$ will be called closed-loop or feedback strategy.
Definition 2.9. Let $G$ be a finite group, and $\mathcal{C}$ a fusion category. A categorical action of $G$ on $\mathcal{C}$ is a monoidal functor $\rho:\underline{G}\to\underline{\operatorname{Eq}}(\mathcal{C}),$ where $\underline{G}$ is the monoidal category whose objects are the objects of $G$, and whose morphisms are identities, and $\underline{\operatorname{Eq}}(\mathcal{C})$ is the monoidal category of monoidal auto-equivalences of $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 2.3. A quotient of $\operatorname{Fib}^{*N}$ is a rigid tensor category $\mathcal{C}$, along with a faithful dominant functor $\operatorname{Fib}^{*N}\to\mathcal{C}.$
Definition 2.5. The pivotal fusion category $\mathcal{TT}_{3}$ has six simple objects $\mathbf{1},f^{(2)},\rho,\sigma,\overline{\sigma}$, and $\mu$, with dimensions $1,\left(\frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2}\right)^{3},\frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2},\left(\frac{1+% \sqrt{5}}{2}\right)^{2},\left(\frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2}\right)^{2},$ and $\frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2}$ respectively. The fusion rules are given by $\begin{array}[]{|c|c|c|c|c|c|}\hline\otimes&f^{(2)}&\rho&\sigma&\overline{% \sigma}&\mu\\ \hline f^{(2)}&1{+}2f^{(2)}{+}\sigma{+}\overline{\sigma}{+}\rho{+}\mu&f^{(2)}{% +}\overline{\sigma}&f^{(2)}{+}\sigma{+}\overline{\sigma}{+}\mu&f^{(2)}{+}% \sigma{+}\overline{\sigma}{+}\rho&f^{(2)}{+}\sigma\\ \hline\rho&f^{(2)}{+}\sigma&1{+}\rho&f^{(2)}&\overline{\sigma}{+}\mu&\overline% {\sigma}\\ \hline\sigma&f^{(2)}{+}\sigma{+}\overline{\sigma}{+}\rho&\sigma{+}\mu&f^{(2)}{% +}\overline{\sigma}&1{+}f^{(2)}{+}\mu&f^{(2)}\\ \hline\overline{\sigma}&f^{(2)}{+}\sigma{+}\overline{\sigma}{+}\mu&f^{(2)}&1{+% }f^{(2)}{+}\rho&f^{(2)}{+}\sigma&\overline{\sigma}{+}\rho\\ \hline\mu&f^{(2)}{+}\overline{\sigma}&\sigma&\sigma{+}\rho&f^{(2)}&1{+}\mu\\ \hline\end{array}$
Definition 4.2. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a quotient of $\operatorname{Fib}^{*3}$. We say a word in $\mathcal{C}$ is cyclic if the letters are tri-alternating.
Definition 2.7. We say a quotient of $\operatorname{Fib}^{*N}$ is symmetric if there is a monoidal auto-equivalence mapping the generators $\tau_{1}\mapsto\tau_{2}\mapsto\cdots\mapsto\tau_{N}\mapsto\tau_{1}.$
Definition 2.1. We write $\operatorname{Fib}$ for the pivotal fusion category with the dimension of $\tau$ equal to $\frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2}$, and we write $\overline{\operatorname{Fib}}$ for the fusion category with the dimension of $\tau$ equal to $\frac{1-\sqrt{5}}{2}$.
Definition 2.6. We say a quotient of $\operatorname{Fib}^{*N}$ is full if $\tau_{i}\cong\tau_{j}$ implies $i=j$.
Definition 2.10. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a fusion category with a categorical $G$ action $\rho$, and let $\omega\in H^{3}(G,\mathbb{C}^{\times})$. We define the semi-direct product category $\mathcal{C}\overset{\omega}{\rtimes}G$ as the abelian category $\mathcal{C}\overset{\omega}{\rtimes}G:=\bigoplus_{G}\mathcal{C},$ with tensor product $(X_{1},g_{1})\otimes(X_{2},g_{2}):=(X_{1}\otimes\rho(g_{1})[X_{2}],g_{1}g_{2}),$ and associator $[(X_{1},g_{1})\otimes(X_{2},g_{2})]\otimes(X_{3},g_{3})\to(X_{1},g_{1})\otimes% [(X_{2},g_{2})\otimes(X_{3},g_{3})]$ given by the isomorphism $\omega_{g_{1},g_{2},g_{3}}\operatorname{id}_{X_{1}}\otimes\tau^{g_{1}}_{X_{2},% \rho(g_{2})[X_{3}]}\circ\operatorname{id}_{X_{1}}\otimes\operatorname{id}_{% \rho(g_{1})[X_{2}]}\otimes\mu_{g1,g2}.$ Here $\tau^{g_{1}}$ is the tensorator for the monoidal functor $\rho(g_{1})$, and $\mu$ is the tensorator for the monoidal functor $\rho$.
Definition 2.4. A finite quotient of $\operatorname{Fib}^{*N}$ is a quotient that has finitely many simple objects.
Definition 2.22. [14, VII.3.] Consider $\eta,\eta^{\prime}\in\mathcal{E}_{\mathcal{C}}^{n}(C,A)$, $E:=\overline{\eta}\in\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{n}\left(C,A\right)$, $E^{\prime}:=\overline{\eta^{\prime}}\in\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{n}% \left(C,A\right)$, and let $\eta=\eta_{n}\cdots\eta_{1}$ and $\eta^{\prime}=\eta^{\prime}_{n}\cdots\eta^{\prime}_{1}$ be the natural decompositions of $\eta$ and $\eta^{\prime}$. (1) Given $\alpha\in\operatorname{Hom}{}_{\mathcal{C}}(A,A^{\prime})$, we define $\alpha E:=\alpha\overline{\eta_{n}}\cdots\overline{\eta_{1}}\mbox{.}$ (2) Given $\gamma\in\operatorname{Hom}{}_{\mathcal{C}}(C^{\prime},C)$, we define $E\gamma:=\overline{\eta_{n}}\cdots\overline{\eta_{1}}\gamma\mbox{.}$ (3) We define the sum of extensions of length $n$ in the following way $E+E^{\prime}:=\nabla_{A}\left(E\oplus E^{\prime}\right)\Delta_{C}\mbox{.}$
Definition 2.14. [11, IV.9.] For $n\geq 1$ and $A,C\in\mathcal{C}$, we consider the class $\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{n}\left(C,A\right):=\mathcal{E}_{\mathcal{C}% }^{n}(C,A)/\equiv\mbox{,}$ whose elements will be called extensions of length $n$ with $C$ and $A$ as right and left ends. Let $\overline{\eta}$ denote the equivalence class of $\eta\in\mathcal{E}_{\mathcal{C}}^{n}(C,A)$. An extension morphism from $\overline{\eta}$ to $\overline{\eta^{\prime}}$ is just a morphism from $\eta$ to $\eta^{\prime}$.
Definition 3.5. Let $I$ be a small category and $\mathcal{C}$ be an abelian category. It is said that a family of objects and morphisms $\left(M_{i},f_{\alpha}\right)_{i\in I,\alpha\in\mbox{Hom}_{I}}$ is a direct system if there is a functor $F:I\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$ such that $F(i)=M_{i}\,\forall i\in I$ and $F(\alpha)=f_{\alpha}\,\forall\alpha\in\mbox{Hom}_{I}$.
Definition 2.11. [14, VII.1.] For $E,E^{\prime}\in\operatorname{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}\left(C,A\right)$, the sum extension of $E$ and $E^{\prime}$ is $E+E^{\prime}:=\nabla_{A}\left(E\oplus E^{\prime}\right)\Delta_{C}\mbox{.}$
Definition 3.3. [15, 1.4.] Let $\mathcal{C}$ and $I$ be categories, with $I$ small. Let $F:I\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$ be a functor and $X\in\mathcal{C}$. A family of morphisms $\left\{\alpha_{i}:X\rightarrow F(i)\right\}_{i\in I}$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is compatible with $F$, if $\alpha_{j}=F(\lambda)\alpha_{i}$ for every $\lambda:i\rightarrow j$ in $I$. The limit (or projective limit) of $F$ is an object $\lim F\in\mathcal{C}$ together with a compatible family of morphisms $\left\{\mu_{i}:\lim F\rightarrow F(i)\right\}_{i\in I}$ such that for any compatible family of morphisms $\left\{\gamma_{i}:X\rightarrow F(i)\right\}_{i\in I}$ there is a unique morphism $\gamma:X\rightarrow\lim F$ such that $\gamma_{i}=\mu_{i}\gamma$ for every $i\in I$.
Definition 3.8. [15, 2.8.3.] An Ab4 category is an Ab3 category $\mathcal{C}$ satisfying the following condition: (Ab4): for every set of monomorphisms $\left\{f_{i}:X_{i}\rightarrow Y_{i}\right\}_{i\in I}$ in $\mathcal{C}$, the morphism $\bigoplus_{i\in I}f_{i}$ is a monomorphism.
Definition 2.1. [14, VII.1.] Let $C\in\mathcal{C}$, and $\alpha:A\rightarrow B$, $\alpha^{\prime}:A^{\prime}\rightarrow B^{\prime}$ be morphisms in $\mathcal{C}$. We set the following notation: (1) $\nabla_{C}:=\left(\begin{smallmatrix}1_{C}&1_{C}\end{smallmatrix}\right):C% \oplus C\rightarrow C\mbox{;}$ (2) $\Delta_{C}:=\left(\begin{smallmatrix}1_{C}\\ 1_{C}\end{smallmatrix}\right):C\rightarrow C\oplus C\mbox{;}$ (3) $\alpha\oplus\alpha^{\prime}:=\left(\begin{smallmatrix}\alpha&0\\ 0&\alpha^{\prime}\end{smallmatrix}\right):A\oplus A^{\prime}\rightarrow B% \oplus B^{\prime}\mbox{.}$
